This update of TalkBack has integrated a number of improvements.

Speak the phonetic transcription of letters when they are long pressed on the keyboard, or when navigating through text by character. This option is enabled by default, but can be disabled through TalkBack Settings.

TalkBack pronounces hints for available actions during linear navigation after 1 second delay.

Navigation method (by character/by word/by line etc) is kept even after focus is moved to other nodes. Previously it was cleared after each focus move.

Default Settings were changed for new users:
 -Resume and Suspend TalkBack by long pressing up and down volume buttons is enabled
 -Show Context menu as lists
 -Sound (earcon) volume is reduced from 100 to 50 percent relative to media volume

Only the dialog title is pronounced when new dialog is shown on screen. Previously, the whole dialog was read.

Input fields are announced as currently editing only if the software keyboard is shown.

TalkBack on, suspended, resumed states are announced

We have also fixed a number of bugs

Switch Access lets you scan and select items using one or more switches.

This version of TalkBack includes changes to the default accessibility gestures.

The up-then-down gesture will allow you to move to the first item on the screen, and the down-then-up gesture will move to the last item.

The reading granularity can now be changed by focusing an item, then selecting a granularity from the local context menu.

You can change the actions performed by these gestures in TalkBack Settings.

This version of TalkBack includes changes to the default accessibility gestures.\n\nThe up gesture now moves to the previous navigation setting, and the down gesture now moves to the next navigation setting.

This version of TalkBack includes changes to the default accessibility gestures. The actions associated with these gestures can be customized within TalkBack settings. When Explore by touch is enabled, you can use the following gestures to perform certain actions.\n\n%1$s

When TalkBack is on, your device provides spoken feedback to help blind and low-vision users. For example, it describes what you touch, select, and activate.\n\nIf you have turned TalkBack on accidentally, turn it off by tapping the switch until the green outline is around it, then double-tapping it. Do the same interaction for the resulting confirmation dialog.

When enabled, Explore by touch lets you hear what\'s under your finger. Move your finger over the items in the center of your screen. After you have explored five items, the lesson will continue.
Item 7 activated. Find and activate Next button to continue
To activate the last item you heard, double-tap anywhere. Find Item 7 and activate it now. After that, activate Next to continue.

TalkBack lessons are arranged similarly. The top area has the lesson, which you can explore and read at any time. It also has a Tutorial Home button in the top left corner. The middle has a practice area. The bottom has a progress indicator, and lesson navigation buttons. Activate Next now to continue.
You can also explore by swiping the screen with your finger. Swiping left generally explores up and to the left, while swiping right explores down and to the right. Try it now.
To hear what\'s under your finger, move it across the screen. Double-tap anywhere to activate what you hear. Swipe left or right to explore.

To scroll through a vertical list, find a list item, then move two fingers up or down. To scroll through a horizontal list, find a list item, then move two fingers left or right.
You can jump forward or backward in a list using a shortcut. To jump forward, move one finger right then left in a single motion. To jump back, move one finger left then right. Give it a try here.
Scroll by sliding two fingers up or down. Jump forward by moving one finger right then left. Jump back by moving one finger left then right.
Two-finger scrolling, jumping forward and backward
Menu options are listed vertically in the middle of the screen. Try exploring. When you are done, activate Cancel.

TalkBack has two different menus. The first, the Global TalkBack menu, always contains the same commands. You can activate it by moving a single finger down then right in a single motion, then raising your finger. Activate a practice version now.

The second menu is the Local TalkBack menu. The items in this menu are different depending on what you last heard. You can activate this menu by moving a single finger up then right in a single motion, then raising your finger. Activate a practice menu now.
Global TalkBack Menu: Down then right. Local TalkBack Menu: Up then right
Move your finger down then right to activate the Global TalkBack menu. Move your finger up then right to activate the Local TalkBack menu.
Global TalkBack menu, local TalkBack menu

TalkBack lets you control whether text is read to you a paragraph, a line, a word, or a character at a time. Reading by character can help with spelling. Set the text navigation rate to characters by tapping on the text below, then swiping up and down.
Explore the reading rate options listed vertically here. Find and activate the Read by character option.
You are now reading by character. Select the sample text, then swipe right to read by character.
Change the text navigation rate by swiping up and down. Read the next character in the sample text by swiping right.

Here\'s some sample text for TalkBack practice. \"Where is Kansas?\" asked the man, with surprise. \"I don\'t know,\" replied Dorothy sorrowfully, \"but it is my home, and I\'m sure it’s somewhere.\"\n\n\"Very likely. Well, Oz can do anything; so I supposed he will find Kansas for you. But first you must get to see him, and that will be a hard task; for the Great Wizard does not like to see anyone, and he usually has his own way. But what do YOU want?\" he continued, speaking to Toto.

With TalkBack, you can use an edit box to type, select, and edit text. To activate an edit box, double-tap it. After you activate an edit box, a keyboard becomes available at the bottom of the screen. You can dismiss the keyboard by tapping the Back button. Try activating the edit box now. When you are done, activate Next, which is now above the keyboard.

To type, activate the edit box and move your finger across the onscreen keyboard. When you hear the desired character, lift your finger to activate it. Try activating and typing in the edit box below.
Part 2: Typing in an edit box

You can move a cursor using the volume buttons on your device, or through the Local TalkBack menu. With the Cursor control option in this menu, you can also select, cut, copy, or paste text. Activate the edit box below, and move the cursor around the sample text.
